On notes and professors

  • How I take notes: Divide a paper into two columns and a header. Label the upper right with the class, date, lecture number, and topic. Write reminders and todo items in the header. If non-class related thoughts come up in class, add a box in the lower right corner and add them there. Other methods in this video.

  • How to make use of professors. But in addition, no matter what you’re interested in, your professor would probably love to work with you to get better at it. Go talk to them!

A formal critique

  • People don’t have the processing power to fully analyze every choice, so how can they maximize?

via GIPHY

One response

By Milton Friedman:

  1. People may not consciously analyze, but they are like pool players. Pool players don’t calculate the physics of every shot, they build up experience over time that allows them to make the best shot.
  2. Competition would weed out people who don’t optimize (i.e. over time they wouldn’t reproduce.)

Criticism of Friedman’s argument

We value differently than price

P&R Video

  • A naive economist (or economics critic) would say Ron Swanson’s gift of $20 is better, why?
  • Because since we optimize utility, we know best how to use $20.
  • But actually the value of the gift is not the money, but the signal that they know us right?
  • Imposes an additional cost on the gift giver of trying to find a meaningful gift to “demonstrate” knowing.

Utility

Utility - the advantage, pleasure, or fulfillment a person gains from obtaining or consuming a good or service.

  • Okay but how do people make choices to maximize their utility? How do we make choices to be happy?
  • People choose between goods to maximize utility subject to their budget constraint.

Indifference

  • You are indifferent between two bundles of goods if they both have the same utility to you.

Example of indifference

  1. Think of your favorite shoes and hats.
  2. Suppose you have 3 pairs of awesome shoes and 6 hats. How many hats would you give up to have a fourth pair of shoes?
  3. Suppose you’d give up 3 hats for a 4th pair of shoes. Then you’d be indifferent between \(\{3 \; \mbox{shoes}, 6 \;\mbox{hats} \}\) and \(\{4 \; \mbox{shoes}, 3 \;\mbox{hats} \}\)

  • Marginal rate of transformation - The quantity of some good that must be sacrificed to acquire one additional unit of another good. At any point, it is the slope of the feasible frontier. The Economy on MRT.

Definitions

  • Indifference Curve - A curve of the points which indicate the combinations of goods that provide a given level of utility to the individual. The Economy on the indifference curve and MRS

  • Marginal Rate of Substitution - The trade-off that a person is willing to make between two goods. At any point, this is the slope of the indifference curve. The Economy on the indifference curve and MRS

  • Marginal rate of transformation - The quantity of some good that must be sacrificed to acquire one additional unit of another good. At any point, it is the slope of the feasible frontier. The Economy on MRT.
